<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,1205,1727]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,558,1275,1301]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Distribution and ecology:—</emphasis>
Locally common in mountains of 
<collectingCountry box="[990,1128,1276,1302]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1146,1294,1276,1302]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1313,1432,1276,1302]" name="Colombia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,278,1314,1340]" name="Venezuela" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[291,393,1314,1340]" name="Ecuador" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[406,464,1314,1340]" name="Peru" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Peru</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[530,623,1314,1340]" name="Bolivia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
. Found in open habitats in humid montane forests, along roads, on landslides, and near streams, (800–) 
<quantity box="[570,737,1353,1379]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.325" metricValueMax="3.25" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="m" value="2325.0" valueMax="3250.0" valueMin="1400.0">1400–3250 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,1205,1727]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,307,1391,1417]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Notes:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nakai" authorityYear="1950" baseAuthorityName="Mett." box="[307,562,1392,1417]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubiginosus">
<emphasis box="[307,562,1392,1417]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Sticherus rubiginosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to a group of five closely related species, which also includes 
<taxonomicName class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Gleichenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brittonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">S. brittonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Copeland" authorityYear="1947" baseAuthorityName="Christ" box="[272,462,1431,1456]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strictissimus">
<emphasis box="[272,462,1431,1456]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">S. strictissimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ching" authorityYear="1940" baseAuthorityName="Kaulf." box="[480,629,1431,1456]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="farinosus">
<emphasis box="[480,629,1431,1456]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">S. farinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lellinger" authorityYear="1984" baseAuthorityName="Maxon &amp; C. V. Morton" box="[701,868,1431,1456]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Gleichenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="boliviensis">
<emphasis box="[701,868,1431,1456]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">S. boliviensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. All five species have been considered to be conspecific (e.g., by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tryon, R. M. &amp; Stolze, R. G." box="[395,644,1469,1495]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 122" refId="ref34267" refString="Tryon, R. M. &amp; Stolze, R. G. (1989) Pteridophyta of Peru. Part II. 13. Pteridaceae - 15. Dennstaedtiaceae. Fieldiana Botany, n. s. 22: 1 - 122." type="book chapter" year="1989">Tryon &amp; Stolze 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ostergaard A. &amp; Ollgaard, E." box="[656,994,1469,1495]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" pagination="107 - 169" refId="ref33047" refString="Ostergaard A., Ollgaard, E. &amp; B. (2001) Gleicheniaceae. In Harling, G. &amp; Andersson, L. (eds.), Flora of Ecuador 66: 107 - 169." type="journal article" year="2001">Østergaard &amp; Øllgaard 2001</bibRefCitation>
). They all have lanceolate branch and bud scales with a marginal to central pattern of scale darkening, but they differ in the degree of separation of the segments, the shape of the midvein scales, the prominence of the veinlets, and to some degree, in the pattern of scale darkening. Most collections from the complex surrounding 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nakai" authorityYear="1950" baseAuthorityName="Mett." box="[1080,1254,1585,1610]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubiginosus">
<emphasis box="[1080,1254,1585,1610]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">S. rubiginosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can readily be placed into the five species we propose. However, there are some specimens, especially from 
<collectingCountry box="[1248,1337,1624,1650]" name="Bolivia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, that are either intermediate between species or show a unique combination of characters. Since these specimens do not form a uniform group or show an indication of hybridity, they cannot be delimited as a distinct species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
